Introduction¶

This project was related to the Playground Series Season 3 Episode 8, hosted by Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/playground-series-s3e8. A couple of notes as you walk through the notebook:

1) I purposely constrained myself to only use generalized linear models. Many in the competition used various ensemble models (for good reason) and outperformed my final submission, but this project is meant to showcase the multitudes of ways one can leverage linear models. It covers feature engineering, data transformations, model tuning, model evaluation and model selection. I believe it is a good notebook to understand my thought process as I try to tackle a problem relatively quickly.

2) This is by no means exhaustive. I didn't have time to leverage kernel regression or quantile regression during this project, which I believe would have improved the performance of the model.

3) This notebook contains only the necessary thought process leading to the final model. There were other directions I evaluated during the model creation (such as additional features or parameters within categorical variables) that I did not include within this notebook for brevities sake.

4) The initial linear model creation, feature selection/experimentation and evaluation was done primarily as experimentation. I find the best way to learn about the data is to actually play with the data, rather than gridsearch through all of the possibilities of models to find the best one. With that caveat, I will note that the first 6 models developed were done without much consideration for multicollinearity, partial F-tests etc. It was primarily an exercise to see what factors were in play and how the model performance reacts to different changes. Likewise, the final submission does not consider those aspects of model building. It would have been cumbersome to implement those considerations to model design I was implementing and I made the decision to disregard them in order to get a submission in by the competitions completion.

Response Variable Distribution¶

This will help inform us on the model we are trying to build. In linear models, we will often transform the response variable to fit a particular distribution that we assume our estimates will fit within.

This is either a log-normal distribution or an exponential distribution, hinting that we will likely have to perform some kind of transformation or alternative to basic linear regression model in the future. We perform 3 common transformations here that could have theoretically generated a normal distribution and can use them to our regression techniques.

So far, we have generated multiple insights from our data, related to the categorical variables: 1) Our sample of training data has more higher cut quality gems than other groups
2) Our sample of training data has a "normal" distribution of color gems.
3) The clarity of our gems appears to be more weighted towards those gems of poor quality, rather than higher quality.
4) As the color and clarity increase, the price of the gems increases.
5) As the cut of the gem increases the price appears, paradoxically, to decrease.

These categorical variables imply that we might be able to model the price of the gems via creating multiple linear regression models based on the differet combinations of categorical variables. (n(clarity) x n(color) x n(color)) which would be 280 different models. This might be possible with our sample size, but we should investigate the sample sizes of the subcategories of diamonds. These subcategories could explain why the cut of the gems increase in quality appears to cause the price to decrease.

Notes & Findings:¶

1) Outliers have been detected in a couple of different places (see scatterplots for highlights).
2) The categorical variables predictive power with price to not seem to follow a logical order when viewed independent of others. Color is the exception. It is likely that this lack of price increase as the percieved quality of the diamonds increases is likely due to interaction between clarity and cut and other variables.
3) The overall distribution of gems seems to be weighted more towards the 'higher' quality side. Traditionally, we might think that as a gems rarity increases, the more valuable it gets - but in our sample size, the "rarer" gems might actually be of lower quality.
4) We have concerns about the number of records in certain subsamples of our data.

Feature Engineering / Removal of Outliers¶

One of our concerns was to the actual values of x,y,z in our model. From both external research on gems as well as the data itself, we make a quick model of the x,y,z variables, assuming carat is correct. Generally speaking, the carat is equivalent to x y z / 163.3406 with z being roughly equivalent to .6185 of the x and y values, which are equivalent. We can use this heuristics to impute values for x,y,z in the case that they are either ommitted or obviously incorrect.

def add_features(df):
    df = df.copy()
    
    df['x_estimate'] =  np.cbrt(df['carat'] * 163.3406 / .6185)
    df['y_estimate'] =  np.cbrt(df['carat'] * 163.3406 / .6185)
    df['z_estimate'] = df['y_estimate']*.6185
    df['carat_estimate'] = df['z_estimate'] * df['x_estimate'] * df['y_estimate']
    #replace x,y,z if the x,y,z are blank
    df['z'] = np.where(df['z'] == 0, df['z_estimate'], df['z'])
    df['x'] = np.where(df['x'] == 0, df['x_estimate'], df['x'])
    df['y'] = np.where(df['y'] == 0, df['y_estimate'], df['y'])
    #replace x,y,z if the values of x,y,z are outside of 20% of our expectation
    df['x'] = np.where(df['x'] / df['y'] < .8, df['x_estimate'], df['x'])
    df['x'] = np.where(df['x'] / df['y'] > 1.2, df['x_estimate'], df['x'])
    
    df['y'] = np.where(df['y'] / df['x'] > 1.2, df['y_estimate'], df['y'])
    df['y'] = np.where(df['y'] / df['x'] > .8, df['y_estimate'], df['y'])
    
    df['z'] = np.where(df['z'] / df['y'] > .8, df['z_estimate'], df['z'])
    df['z'] = np.where(df['z'] / df['y'] < .4, df['z_estimate'], df['z'])
    
    df["surface_area"] = 2 * (df["x"] * df["y"] + df["y"] * df["z"] + df["z"] * df["x"])
    df['volume'] = df['x'] * df['y'] * df['z']
    
    df['GirdleEstimate'] = (df['x'] + df['y']) / 2 
    
    df['DepthEstimate'] = df['z'] / df['GirdleEstimate']
    df['TabletoGirdle'] = df['table'] / df['GirdleEstimate'] 
    

    df['carat_size1'] = np.where(df['carat'] < .5, "A.0-.5",\
                                np.where(df['carat'] < 1, "B.5-1",\
                                np.where(df['carat'] < 1.49, "C.1-1.5",\
                                np.where(df['carat'] < 1.99, "D.1.5-2","E.2.0+"))))
    return df
In [26]:
def remove_outliers(df):
    '''remove elements that contain 0s'''
    df = df.copy()
    outlier_indexes = df[(df[['x','y','z']] == 0).any(axis=1)].index
    return outlier_indexes

def get_model_diagnostics(data):
    '''Assumes that the columns are named error, actual and pred'''
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, nrows=3)
    #normality
    sns.histplot(x = 'error', data = data, ax = ax[0,0]).set(title=f"Normality {x}")
    #linear relationship
    sns.scatterplot(x ='actual', y = 'pred', data = data, ax = ax[0,1]).set(title="Linear Relationship")

    #constant variance
    sns.scatterplot(x = 'pred', y = 'error',data = data, ax = ax[1,0]).set(title="Var: Residuals v. Preds")
    sns.scatterplot(x = 'actual', y = 'error',data = data, ax = ax[1,1]).set(title="Var: Residuals v. Actual")
    
    #constant variance
    sns.scatterplot(x = 'carat', y ='error', data = data, ax=ax[2,0]).set(title="Variance: Carat vs. Residual")
    fig.delaxes(ax[2,1])
    fig.tight_layout()

Model Building¶

From here on out we will be iterating through multiple different variations of linear regressions in an attempt to minimize our RMSE, which was the evaluation metric for this competition.

For organizations sake, we can store the RMSE of each model as well as several of the pertinent diagnostics for each model in a dictionary that we can call later in the modeling process to assess our progress.

Linear Regression w/ transformations¶

In [28]:
#reload training data 
train_data = pd.read_csv("train.csv")
test_data = pd.read_csv("test.csv")

cols = ['carat','cut','clarity','color','volume','surface_area','table','depth']
outliers = remove_outliers(train_data)
train_data.drop(outliers,inplace=True)
train_data = add_features(train_data)

We start by creating very basic models with one predictor in order to understand the relationship between our primary predicting variable (carat) and the price of a gem. We iterate and add complexity to our models in an attempt to improve our models predictive power.

This comes on the backdrop of creating a "good" model. We evaluate each model using the main assumptions of linear regression: 1) Normal distribution of error terms
2) Constant Variance
3) Linear Relationship

Details on the assumptions (there are a few others) we are driving towards can be found https://www.statology.org/linear-regression-assumptions/

Additional helper functions¶

One of the other issues we will run through as we test for the overall significance of our models is the fact that sklearn does not provide a fstat calculation for overall regression signficance. We can create one quickly.

In [29]:
def fstat_linear(X_train, y_train, preds):
    '''n: Sample size,
       k: number of predictors
       '''
    N = len(X_train)
    K = len(X_train.columns)
    r2 = r2_score(y_train, preds)
    return (r2/(1-r2))*((N-K-1)/K)

#model1
#basicModel
#import data
train_data = pd.read_csv("train.csv")
test_data = pd.read_csv("test.csv")
outliers = remove_outliers(train_data)
train_data.drop(outliers,inplace=True) 
X_train = train_data[['carat']]
y_train = train_data['price']

model_1 = LinearRegression()
model_1.fit(X_train,y_train)
preds = model_1.predict(X_train)
model_1_residuals = (y_train - preds)
model1_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, preds)


sns.scatterplot(y=model_1_residuals,x=X_train['carat']).set(ylabel="residuals")
print("Model RMSE is ...", np.sqrt(model1_mse))
linear_models_diagnostics['Model1'] = {}
linear_models_diagnostics['Model1']['RMSE'] = np.sqrt(model1_mse)
linear_models_diagnostics['Model1']['RSquared'] = r2_score(y_train, preds)
linear_models_diagnostics['Model1']['FScore'] = fstat_linear(X_train, y_train, preds)

Model RMSE is ... 1338.0406450416572

We can see from the above that constant variance is violated. We are more likely to overestimate the price of a gem with a lower carat and under estimate the price of a gem with a higher carat.

Stratifying our Data and Models¶

As noted during early EDA of the response variable, price appears to be some kind of bimodal distribution. At this point, we have created multiple linear models, but all of them have some degree of incorrect fitting. We have performed multiple transformations but our residuals violate constant variance assumptions and we need to solve for our inability to properly model prices at higher carat. Here, we implement a few different stratified linear models, with the core goal of capturing the non-normal distribution of our transformed response variable. Essentially what we want to do is create multiple generalized linear models with flexibility for the design of the model to better fit a subset of our data. In the context of what we have previously discussed - we want our model to be able to better model different subsections of the carat size.

In [51]:
train_data = pd.read_csv("train.csv")
test_data = pd.read_csv("test.csv")
outliers = remove_outliers(train_data)
train_data.drop(outliers,inplace=True)
train_data = add_features(train_data)

Model 1:¶

We create multiple regression models, based on the carat size of the records with no kinds of transformations, and use the combination of the models to undertand that models performance.

In [52]:
#first iteration is w/o any transformations
final_model = {}
multiple_models = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['class','carat','pred','actual'])
for x in train_data['carat_size1'].unique():
    final_model[x] = {}
    temp_df = train_data[train_data['carat_size1'] == x]
    temp_df.reset_index(inplace = True)
    temp_model = LinearRegression()
    temp_x = pd.get_dummies(temp_df[['carat','cut','clarity','color']], columns = ['cut','clarity','color'])
    temp_y = temp_df['price']
    
    #transformations
    #no transformations
    #fit the model
    temp_model.fit(temp_x, temp_y)
    
    #untransformations
    #no need to reverse 
    
    #get predictions and diagnostics
    preds = temp_model.predict(temp_x)
    df=pd.concat([temp_df['carat_size1'],temp_df['carat'],pd.Series(preds) ,temp_y], \
                 axis=1)
    df.set_axis(['class','carat','pred','actual'], axis=1,inplace=True)
    
    df['error'] = df['pred'] - df['actual']
    final_model[x]['MSE'] = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(df['pred'],df['actual']))
    final_model[x]['Model'] = temp_model
    final_model[x]['DF'] = df

Model 2:¶

We perform the same process, but now we transform the price variable using the boxcox methodology. Importantly, we are performing multiple different transformations on our price data. We are assuming that the response variable follows a different distribution at different levels of carats.

In [54]:
#Second iteration w/ target transform

strat_model_target_xformed = {}
multiple_models = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['class','carat','pred','actual','preds_xformed','actual_xformed'])
for x in sorted(train_data['carat_size1'].unique()):
    strat_model_target_xformed[x] = {}
    temp_df = train_data[train_data['carat_size1'] == x]
    temp_df.reset_index(inplace = True)
    temp_model = LinearRegression()
    temp_x = pd.get_dummies(temp_df[['carat','cut','clarity','color']], columns = ['cut','clarity','color'])
    temp_y = temp_df['price']
    
    #transformations
    temp_y, lamb = boxcox(temp_y) 
    
    #fit the model
    temp_model.fit(temp_x, temp_y)
    
    #get predictions and diagnostics
    preds = temp_model.predict(temp_x)
    #reverse transformations
    preds_xformed = preds
    actual_xformed = temp_y
    preds = inv_boxcox(preds, lamb)
    temp_y = inv_boxcox(temp_y, lamb)

    df=pd.concat([temp_df['carat_size1'],temp_df['carat'],pd.Series(preds) ,pd.Series(temp_y),pd.Series(preds_xformed) ,pd.Series(actual_xformed)], \
                 axis=1)
    df.set_axis(['class','carat','pred','actual','preds_xformed','actual_xformed'], axis=1,inplace=True)
    
    df['error'] = df['pred'] - df['actual']
    strat_model_target_xformed[x]['Model'] = temp_model
    strat_model_target_xformed[x]['DF'] = df
    strat_model_target_xformed[x]['lambda_y'] = lamb
    strat_model_target_xformed[x]['MSE'] = np.sqrt(np.mean(df['error']**2))
In [55]:
combinatory2_mse = []
for x in train_data['carat_size1'].unique():
    combinatory2_mse.append(list(strat_model_target_xformed[x]['DF']['error']**2))
errors = [x for l in combinatory2_mse for x in l]
errors = [x for x in errors if not np.isnan(x)]
np.sqrt(np.mean(errors))
Out[55]:
613.9893974386822

Once again, our model improves in terms of its RMSE. Please note that several values of our predictions have to be from nans due to the functionality of inverting the boxcox transformation.

    cols = ['carat','cut','color','clarity'\
#             ,'depth','table','surface_area','volume','GirdleEstimate',\
#             'DepthEstimate','TabletoGirdle'\
           ]
    all_vars_y_xformed[x] = {}
    temp_df = train_data[train_data['carat_size1'] == x]
    temp_df.reset_index(inplace = True)
    temp_model = LinearRegression()
    temp_x = pd.get_dummies(temp_df[cols], columns = ['cut','clarity','color'])
    temp_y = temp_df['price']
    
    
    #transformations
    temp_y, lamb = boxcox(temp_y) 
    temp_x['carat'], lamb2 = boxcox(temp_x['carat'])
    #fit the model
    temp_model.fit(temp_x, temp_y)
    
    #get predictions and diagnostics
    preds = temp_model.predict(temp_x)
    #reverse transformations
    preds_xformed = preds
    actual_xformed = temp_y
    preds = inv_boxcox(preds, lamb)
    temp_y = inv_boxcox(temp_y, lamb)
    df=pd.concat([temp_df['carat_size1'],temp_df['carat'],pd.Series(preds) ,pd.Series(temp_y),pd.Series(preds_xformed) ,pd.Series(actual_xformed)], \
                 axis=1)
    df.set_axis(['class','carat','pred','actual','preds_xformed','actual_xformed'], axis=1,inplace=True)
    df = df[~df.isna().any(axis=1)]
    df['error'] = df['actual'] - df['pred']
    
    all_vars_y_xformed[x]['Model'] = temp_model
    all_vars_y_xformed[x]['DF'] = df
    all_vars_y_xformed[x]['lambda_y'] = lamb
    all_vars_y_xformed[x]['MSE'] = np.sqrt(np.mean(df['error']**2))

Critique and Commentary¶

This was a difficult set of data due to the sampling issues associated with it. I'll touch on a few.

1) I wanted to use downsampling / upsampling in order to solve for what I perceived to be an issue in the subsamples sizing noted within this script several times. I believe that the models are being influenced by outsized numbers of certain cut/clarity/color combinations, which continiously cause issues with the accuracy of the model when it comes to other cut/clarity/color combinations which have lower weights within any individual subset. The level of upsampling necessary was too much for my machine to handle and downsampling did not yield improvement.

2) Feature engineering and outlier removal could have been more robust. I prioritized iterating within my models to understand what the underlying issues were with my models vs. trying to synthesize a perfect dataset. Kaggle does not release details on the outliers or the generative process for creating the data, so I feel fairly convinced that there was some data-integrity issues that I missed.

3) As noted in the introduction, I attempted many, many other generalized linear models during this process that I did not include in this final notebook. I trained mutliple different models based on the cut/clarity/color of the gem or the combination of the three. These models took exceptionally long to generate and did not truly improve the performance of the models.

4) One key learning for me was the ability to quickly iterate between models. I would have liked to have formalized the pipeline process and feature selection process in some kind of class/method so that I could have more easily understood where my models needed to be tuned. Using linear regression in python can sometimes be a bit limiting (unlike in R, where one has access to many more statistical tuning tools), so I would have liked to have set up a framework initially to more quickly iterate. A good example of that is the function that I used to visualize the assumptions of linear regression mentioned in the intro. That functionality is native in R.

5) Finally, something I will include in subsequent iterations of this work, will a more robust analysis of the different models. I will add checks for VIF, partial F-test model comparisons etc. As noted in the introduction, much of the initial model building was done more as experimentation rather than robust model selection, but it is something that should be interwoven throughout the process in future iterations to aid in my understanding of each individual models performance and improvement relative to others.

Submission Performance¶

The final model submitted did perform well overall, placing about 10% off from the best performing models, which as shown on the kaggle leaderboard, generally leverage a host of ensemble models which have been tuned exeptionally rigorously. This exercise was not about finding the best performing model, but rather attempting to form the best linear model possible. I feel that these linear models represent nearly as good as a performing model as can be created, without the exceptional ambiguity of training multiple ensemble models with all features and without a fundamental understanding for the reasons behind their performance.

The only additional part of the final model that I did not include is that, due to the nature of boxcox transformations, several predictions were illogical and were replaced with an exceptionally simple KNN script (these prices were negative and only occured <5 times).
